The pierogies were both nice. Bryndza (a dry Slovakian cheese which taste resembles parmesan) & potato pierogies were tasty.  This was also the first time I ever tried  dessert pierogies, in this case chocolate. This is great destination for dining and takeout or if one is passing by from the nearby microbreweries.
One of NYC’s hidden treasures. Incredible food, good drinks, and a heartwarming story (family owned!).

I wish I lived closer so I could go more often! I had Baba’s for the first time about a year ago and they blew me away. I started ordering regularly when they would do cross borough delivery to Manhattan when covid began to impact restaurants. When outdoor dining became easier this summer/fall, I was able to go to the restaurant for the first time and the food, service, and staff were all incredible. They even remembered my name from delivery and Instagram. If you like pierogies, you will LOVE Baba’s.

A HIDDEN GEM. I discovered this place while scrolling aimlessly on Google maps and omg I’m so glad I did! Stopped in tonight for a post-work snack and I’m so impressed. Very friendly service,  the space is super cute, and my order was prepared quickly. The vegan pierogis are incredible and remind me so much of the ones my mom made when I was growing up. 11/10 will definitely be back!  Wish I had a photo to share but we inhaled them too quickly.

I love Baba's. Lots of vegetarian pierogi options. I know it sounds a bit strange, but get the mac and cheese pierogies pan fried. The boiled jalapeno and the boiled potato and cheese are also delicious. Caramelized onions are a must for topping.  Baba's has a small outdoor seating area in front. Take out was prompt and efficient. Hope to stop by again soon.
The food is always fresh and tasty, cashiers gives good customer service. I like the cleanliness and vibes. Would recommend to others.
Absolutely delicious food, and the owners are some of the kindest people I’ve met in New York!
The pierogies were delicious.  Just like I used to get from the old Kiev Diner back during my college days in the early 80's.  I will be stopping by often and so should you!  😃
I order some for pick up n it was only a 10 minute wait and they were super yummy
Best comfort food on 3rd! I love their fried perogies and sausage!
The vegan pierogies are amazing!! Great dipping sauces and customer service. Love it here. Will definitely be back

Baba’s Pierogi’s are melt-in-your-mouth delicious. We ate outside tonight and enjoyed the potato pierogis, the Octoberfest special  goulash and a fresh golden beet salad. Plus two excellent Czech beers on tap. The waiter was so friendly and the service was stellar, even during a pandemic when most places are short staffed.    They have so many different pierogis options, it was hard to choose. Can’t wait to go back and try the others. Highly recommend!

I've had Baba's in my list for sometime, and recently started working in the area to discover I was only a few blocks away. The pierogies are outstanding, and the schnitzel bites are.. HOLY SH*T. Honestly, some of the best food I've tried in NY so far. Don't miss it.
Soooooo yummy!  I especially recommend the boiled cheese & potato Pierogies with sautéed mushrooms and caramelized onions.  Fast delivery and excellent food.

This place is a gem! We had a fantastic time at Baba's today. We had the beet salad, fried jalepano and sauerkraut pierogis, and boiled potato and cheese pierogis. Our favorite ended being the jalepano pierogis, most especially with the carmelized onions and hot sauce on top. Service was friendly and we even got $2 off drinks for happy hour. Delicious! What a wonderful place to bring a rambuncous 6 year old and my 93 year old grandmother! We were helped (patiently!) Into the restaurant. Lunch was served quickly, we had sauerkraut, farmers cheese, potato and Mac n'cheese along with beet salad and cucumber salad. We added bacon and carmelized onion. The bacon was amazing! I wasn't thrilled with the onions, but everything else was delicious. This is one of the few places that prides itself on a thinner dough, allowing us to savor the stuffings.

Five stars because the food was awesome and the staff was nice. However, there were a few mistakes with our order. The main issue being that we received one batch of fried pirogi when we had asked for boiled. Not a big deal since the fried were delicious but a bit heavier than we wanted. We took some leftovers home and they did not package the toppings that were remaining. This makes me sad because the toppings were very delicious but also cost extra. We also ordered toppings for both (which cost extra and were as delicious as the pierogis), but when we took our leftovers to go we realized later that they didn’t get put in the leftovers box :( Despite these little things I would still return for the sauerkraut pierogis and the homemade apple sauce :)

I prefer boiled but the owner and customers mostly prefer fried.” And yes, fried was better but boiled grew on me. This is by far the best pierogies I've had in the US. I got some for an event, and we got one tray each of potato and cheese, spinach and feta, and chocolate. The chocolate came with whipped cream which was awesome, and I really enjoyed the potato and cheese. I like these pierogies because the skin is chewy and the inside is creamy, and it's really tasty. The chocolate one was fried, and since we got it delivered, the skin unfortunately was hard by the time we got it; I'd imagine it's much better if I had it at the restaurant itself. The chocolate one wasn't too sweet either which I appreciated. The potato and cheese was really creamy inside, and it was super tasty, a crowd favorite. The spinach and feta flavor was quite strong, but the balance between the spinach and feta was good. These three trays along with delivery was $130, and each tray had 25 pierogies. Price is a bit high, but quality was good; I would definitely consider them again for catering!
I'll probably never be the same. Their food tasted like home. Filled my heart with warmth & flavor. Amazing.
Fantastic quality and freshness. The service was fantastic and sweet. Such a relaxing place to eat.

From vegan to carniterrean and all points in between!  After a lovely cocktail just down the street at Lucky Lucey's (more on them another time), pierogies and kraut and beets (And okay yes,  a killer sausage) were just what the doctor ordered after a rousing day of vintage shopping and hiking through Gowanus.  Baba's pierogies are defined by a yielding and nicely delicate dough. After trying them both boiled and pan-fried,  the fried variation was far and away our preference due to the variety of textures and excellent browning. While every flavor was good, the Spinach and Feta's faint garlicky bite really stood out. Because pierogies are ordered in batches of 5 or 9, unless you're bringing a group it will take several trips to try them all.  Note: f you're looking to seat a large group, the dining room is quite intimate so you may want to call ahead or be prepared to wait awhile.  The kielbasy is awesome. If you partake in meat,  it's a wonderful plate.  A well curated selection of draft beers and wines by the glass make for a sharp accompaniment with generous pours to boot. The Czechvar lager is a wonderful option along with rotating seasonal beers and wines (Get the Gruner Veltliner ;-)  For those so inclined there is a seperate and nicely laid out vegan menu. The staff will go above and beyond to accommodate dietary restrictions as much as possible.
Best pierogis I’ve had to date. Very warm family atmosphere with very friendly staff. Will be visiting whenever I’m in town for sure!

The food was decent,  interesting combinations but expensive for what it is. When I tried to fix it, they refused saying the order already went through, making it seem like it was my fault. They told me customers always change their mind, as if I was tricking them or something, so odd.  Probably wouldn't go back just because 55 dollars for some dumplings is a lot!  You can't mix and match too, fyi.

I just HAD to write this review. My partner and I just moved to Park Slope from East Village where we ate pierogis with some regularity. We decided to try Baba's because of its great prices, reviews, and a menu with some flexibility. We ordered the boiled potato and farmers cheese pierogis topped with mushrooms with sourcream and chive dip and we got kielbasy with homemade saurkraut and fresh horseradish and the cucumber salad. We took our first bites, made eye contact, and ate the rest of the meal in silence because we were engulfed in how delicious everything was!! No joke. Best pierogis I've ever had, the mustard with the kielbasy was perfect... And the service was great. The owner took our order and told us about baba's tea which his grandmother used to make for them, and you can truly feel that this is a family affair. Get that tea.. It's iced rosehip, mint and hibiscus.. Incredible.  I really can't say enough good things and I cannot wait to go back.  I am so excited that it's only two blocks away. Now I'm hungry. See you soon, Baba's.

If you are in Brooklyn and want a good Slovakian meal, this is the place to go. The perogies were amazing. We tried the feta spinach, potato cheese, jalepeno cheese, sauerkraut, and chocolate! All of them were great. We bought a side of horseradish and carmelized onions to go with everything, they added so much flavor. The beer and cider were great too. Everything is fresh and delicious.  We even had to come a second day we liked them so much. Don't be fooled by how small the menu seems. Each perogie is very different and has its own unique flavor. I wish I could go back and try all the perogies they had, but it'll have to wait till next time I'm in New York!

YOU. MUST. EAT. HERE.  First, the place is attended by the family of the owner and right there you’re betting for AWESOME SERVICE! Our waiter spent with us about 15 minutes, we talked about technology, smartphones, big names in the tech industry, security, gaming. Add this to the EXQUISITE PIROGIES and it’s just a great experience.  This place is particularly good for groups if most of the people in your group hasn’t tried pirogies, because there are 8 different fillings and you want to try all of them. The orders come in 2 sizes: A “snack” portion with 5 pirogies for $8.00 or a “meal” portion with 9 pirogies for $10.50... So you only need to bring about 3 friends to try them all.  This was my first time eating pirogies and I must admit that my expectations of Nordic food were really low and that may impact my review, however... I chose this place because of it’s HIGH YELP RATING, so I’m not crazy giving them five starts.  Our waiter proceeded to explain to me how pirogies are the same as concept as empanadas or wontons in other cultures - To make it easy for me to understand.  Since I wanted to experience the whole Nordic culture I went with the Czech beer on tap Czhechvar and proceeded to order different fillings for the pirogies we’d share at the table..  WHICH FILLING? The Spinach & Feta were the best by far with Potato and Cheese in second place.  DO YOU REALLY NEED THE SALAD? Don’t waste that valuable stomach space on the salad unless you need to. We ordered the Golden Beet Salad and the Cucumber Salad and they’re good and tasty and healthy and all of that but in reality, it’s only Golden Beet or Cucumber with some dressing, nothing more.  KIELBASY We were not fans of the kielbasa ($9.75 and it includes sauerkraut). Try it if you must, but the specialty here is pierogies and any stomach space or money you invest in something else, is not the wisest choice.  DESSERT PIROGIES Just because pirogies are so good and sweet pirogies sounds like something you must do while here. The Crunchy Chocolate pirogies ( 5 for $8.50) that I tried were really good, A DELICACY!
Great food, great service, great venue. My only suggestion is to perhaps buy the larger portion. The 5 count is not enough for a meal and at $8+ it's not cheap. But they were good. :)

~ Specializes in pierogies with classic, and non traditional fillings. ~ My favorite one is the Pan Fried Jalapeño. ~ Counter service. ~ Ample amount of Seating. ~ Clean and modern look. ~ Bathroom available. ~ No Wi-Fi. ~ It wasn't hard for me to find parking.  I reckon slavic people aren't as bad as they are portrayed in the movies, nor the food as boring as its reputation would suggest.  Proof: Baba pierogis! from their friendly and helpful service, to their version of the National dish in many slavic countries; pierogies! I was impressed.  Before trying to explain my blissful bite here, a quick note first. For me, a dish made to perfection is the hardest to describe. It is one of my withdrawal symptoms of an "Euphoric Experience" in a restaurant. So when I took the time later that day to write a review, I was obviously still under the influence, so bare with me, as I'm trying my best here...  From a peasant food in the olden times to a national dish in Poland, slovakia, & Ukraine, the pierogi made it's way through thick and thin only to end up in a freezer near you. Not bad for its legacy one might say! Hey, it even has a race named after it, The Great Pierogi Mascot Race. Not to mention a monument in Alberta, Canada. But being such a popular dish doesn't really mean it's easy to find a juicy - freshly made on the spot- Pierogi in the city. So that's why "Baba pierogies" is a game changer! Armed With their secret baba's (grandmother) recipe, they churn out one of the best pierogis I've ever had.  The benefits of walking in to an empty restaurant, with an empty stomach was three fold. Not only was the service really fast - it really comes in handy, when you are hangry -. Or the picture snapping of the place, easy and fun. NBut you also have a chance to talk to one of the family members about their Baba's recipe, and get some tips on local Eateries.  Less than five minutes after ordering my pan fried jalapeño pierogies, the basket came out with nine pieces ($11) a side of bacon bits ($1.25), warm sauerkraut ($1), and Helen's dip ($0.50). The combination was just pure joy. It hit all the right spots, Texture taste wise. I was happy that I decided to go with the pan fried over Boiled; that extra crisp added so much to the filling of the potato, cheddar, and jalapeño, that I had an epiphany of sorts when it comes to the latest sophistication of street food around the world. Especially when the fillings of the pierogi worked so well together, when it's not even the traditional version of it.  But let's not forget the star of the night, the one that worked tirelessly to put all of these flavors under a shining light, and highlight the harmonious flavor profile of the pierogi, the one and only: Helen's dip! Although the ingredients of this dip were simple, Sriracha, lime juice, and mayo. It didn't take away my delight of how perfect the dip / condiment was.  Pro Tip: You don't have to be Polish to become a regular here  ___________  Ps. I can only wish they'll one day bottle the Helen's dip, & sell it on its own. I'll be their first customer.
